# {{lb|en|Barbados|politics}} A [[political]] [[sycophant]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|quotee={{w|Maurice Bishop}}|title=Adams’ election call angers Bishop|newspaper=[[w:The Gleaner (newspaper)|The Daily Gleaner]]|location=Kingston, Jamaica|publisher={{w|Gleaner Company}}|date=10 November 1980|page=5|oclc=12005351|newversion=quoted in|2ndauthor=Tony Thorndike|chapter2=The Political Economy of Independence of the Former Associated States of the Commonwealth Caribbean|editor2=Paul Sutton|title2=Dual Legacies in the Contemporary Caribbean: Continuing Aspects of British and French Domination|series2=Legacies of West Indian Slavery|location2=London|publisher2=[[w:Taylor & Francis|Frank Cass & Co.]]|year2=2005|page2=153|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=5POQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA153|isbn2=978-0-7146-3262-9|passage=Like an expectant dog barking for his supper, he [Barbados Prime Minister [[w:Tom Adams (politician)|Tom Adams]]] rushes in to please his new master [[w:Ronald Reagan|[Ronald] Reagan]] like all good '''yardfowls''' by attacking Grenada.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|editor=Graham Walker|magazine=[[w:The World Today (magazine)|The World Today]]|location=London|publisher=[[w:Chatham House|Royal Institute of International Affairs]]; {{w|Oxford University Press}}|year=1985|page=107|column=1|issn=0043-9134|oclc=1142793404|passage=All Caribbean politicians have a network of supporters and informants, popularly known as ‘'''yard-fowls'''’. The VSN [''Volontaires de la Sécurité Nationale'', or {{w|Tonton Macoute}}] were the '''yard-fowl''' armed.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|editor=Sanka Price, Jr.|title=Politics Barbados: The Guide to the General Election, 1986|location=Bridgetown, Barbados|publisher={{w|Barbados Labour Party}}|year=1986|page=84|oclc=252911074|passage=The peculiar term "'''Yardfowl'''" has been with us for nearly 40 years. Its humble beginnings to present day, this apparently indigenous adjective has gone through its own socioeconomic changes. [...] Meant to convey a derogatory, pejorative connotation, "'''Yardfowl'''" was given immortality by our Calypso King the {{w|Mighty Gabby}}, when he produced a musical tribute, some years ago highlighting this unique Barbadian expression.|brackets=on}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ronald A. Williams|chapter=6|title=Four Saints and an Angel|location=Pittsburgh, Pa.|publisher={{w|Dorrance Publishing Company}}|year=2009|pages=40–41|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=V_DMKDulbgoC&pg=PA41|isbn=978-1-4349-0073-9|passage=A '''yardfowl''', according to Marjorie's St. Euribian dictionary of standard dialect, is anybody who t'ink dat being able to call de prime minister by he first name is a paycheck. In other words, a total jackass.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Editorial: ‘Yardfowl’ here to stay|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318104254/https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/66865/editorial-yardfowl-stay|archivedate=18 March 2020|newspaper=[[w:The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]|location=Bridgetown, Barbados|publisher=Nation Pub. Co.|date=2 May 2015|oclc=17930691|passage=The loathsome use of "'''yardfowl'''" has really never been meant to describe the average member of any political party in Barbados. [...] So "'''yardfowls'''" are generally not the people who will attend the party caucuses or the constituency meetings to ask questions and seek answers. Instead, you would expect those so designated, even by leading members of the political parties, to be the leading hecklers of opponents and to be mindlessly singing the praises of those whom they favour. Their refrain: "Talk yuh talk, I wid you all the way." They represent a unique vociferous brand.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|title=The 1929 Anti-Corruption Act|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318103359/https://barbadostoday.bb/2017/11/03/the-1929-anti-corruption-act/|archivedate=18 March 2020|work=Barbados Today|date=3 November 2017|passage=I was completely paralyzed by the wealth of idiocy on display this week and the complete intellectual impoverishment taking place in this country. Sadly, there is only one article per week and not every '''yardfowl''' is worthy of a decent or printable response.}}
